Flavonoids are widely found in a variety of fruits and vegetables, including citrus fruits and tomatoes (
 Tutunchi et al., 2020). Among the different classes of natural products combined, flavonoids represent the largest group of ACE2 inhibitors. In fact, several studies have previously implicated some flavonoids to possess inhibitory properties against ACE2 activity. For instance, a previous 
 in vivo study showed that apigenin upregulates the expression of the ACE2 gene in spontaneously hypertensive rats (
 Sui et al., 2010). Wei and co-workers also demonstrated that baicalin, a natural flavone, attenuates angiotensin-II induced endothelial dysfunction by modulating ACE2 expression both at mRNA and protein levels (
 Wei et al., 2015). Naringenin, a flavanone found in grape fruit, can also attenuate hypertensive reno-vascular damage 
 in vivo by downregulating the ACE2 expression (
 Wang et al., 2019). These reports highlight a potential of flavonoids in mitigating SARS-CoV-2 viral infection via modulation of ACE2. Notably, as is highlighted later in this review, flavonoids like naringenin, naringin, nobiletin, hesperidin, hesperetin, neo-hesperidin, pinocembrin, quercetin, myricetin, and kaempferol have shown potential ACE2 binding affinity toward the residues that contact S protein of SARS-CoV-2 (
 Chen and Du, 2020; 
 Cheng et al., 2020; 
 GÃ¼ler et al., 2020; 
 Ngwa et al., 2020; 
 Omar et al., 2020; 
 Yang et al., 2020a).
